  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Money laundering is a serious federal crime in the United States, and the penalties can be severe. The laws governing money laundering are primarily found under the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957). The penalties depend on the specific offense and the amount of money involved, but they generally include:\n\n### 1. **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956**\n   - **Offenses:** This section prohibits knowingly engaging in financial transactions involving the proceeds of unlawful activity with the intent to:\n     - Promote criminal activity.\n     - Conceal or disguise the nature, location, source, ownership, or control of the proceeds.\n     - Avoid reporting requirements under federal or state law.\n   - **Penalties:**\n     - **Imprisonment:** Up to 20 years.\n     - **Fines:** Up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction, whichever is greater.\n     - Additional penalties may include forfeiture of property involved in or traceable to the money laundering.\n\n### 2. **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957**\n   - **Offenses:** This section prohibits knowingly engaging in a monetary transaction in criminally derived property valued at more than $10,000, where the property is derived from specified unlawful activity.\n   - **Penalties:**\n     - **Imprisonment:** Up to 10 years.\n     - **Fines:** Up to $250,000 or twice the value of the property involved, whichever is greater.\n     - Property involved in the transaction may also be subject to forfeiture.\n\n### Aggravating Factors:\nPenalties can be enhanced under certain circumstances, such as:\n   - Involvement of large sums of money.\n   - Money laundering related to terrorism or drug trafficking (e.g., penalties under the **Patriot Act** or **Controlled Substances Act**).\n   - Repeat offenses.\n\n### Civil Penalties:\nIn addition to criminal penalties, individuals or entities may face civil fines and forfeiture of assets under federal law.\n\n### Collateral Consequences:\nConvictions for money laundering can also lead to:\n   - Loss of professional licenses.\n   - Difficulty obtaining future employment.\n   - Immigration consequences for non-citizens, including deportation or inadmissibility.\n\nIf you\u2019re facing allegations of money laundering, it is essential to consult with a qualified attorney to understand your rights and potential defenses.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
